President Jacob Zuma will on Saturday lead the commemoration of the 20th anniversary of the Constitution of the Republic of South Africa, the presidency said yesterday.Spokesperson Bongani Ngqulunga said the celebration is an important milestone of one of the most internationally acclaimed, progressive and transformative constitutions in the world .This year marks 20 years since the signing into law of the Constitution by late former president Nelson Mandela in Sharpeville on December 10, 1996. South Africa is renowned for its commitment to the promotion and protection of human rights, locally and globally. We should be proud of this important milestone and reflect on the gains attained by our constitutional democracy for the past 20 years. Our Constitution helps us heal the divisions of the past, and pave the way forward for a democratic open society, Ngqulunga said.Zuma is expected to address the commemoration at the George Thabe Sports Ground in Sharpeville, Gauteng.Proceedings will commence with the signing of a pledge by the president and other dignitaries at the Constitution Square at the Vereeniging Civic Centre, followed by the laying of wreaths at the Sharpeville Memorial Site and public address by Zuma.It is expected that Zuma will be accompanied by chief justice Mogoeng Mogoeng and the heads of the legislature, the speaker of the National Assembly, Baleka Mbete, and chairperson of the National Council of Provinces, Thandi Modise.TNA Reporternews@thenewage.co.za